				\begin{document}$${e}^{2}/h$$\end{document}e2/h. The contradiction was resolved in a seminal paper by Kane, Fisher and Polchinski22. Starting from a bosonisation of the original channels in a chiral Luttinger liquid (cLL) frame20,24, they show that the Coulomb coupling between the channels gives rise to two bosonic eigenmodes: a (quasi-)charge mode propagating downstream and a (quasi-)neutral mode propagating upstream. In a second step, they found that the addition of short-range random inter-channel tunneling, as shown in Fig. 1b, is essential to restore the 2/3 conductance. The tunneling was shown to stabilize the (now fully) charged mode and the (now fully) neutral mode when the conductor length is greater than a disorder-dependent charge equilibration length \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
