				\begin{document}$${l}_{{eq}.}$$\end{document}leq., typically a few microns, see Fig.  S3b in the Supplementary. The non-observation of counter-propagating modes in 100 μm wide edge-channel resonators was long-noted in ref. 33. The charge mode damping was attributed to absorption in the bulk33,34. While in ref. 33 the >300 mK temperature lead to finite bulk conductivity, in the present work done at 20 mK, the exponentially vanishing bulk conductivity makes incoherent tunneling processes along the 2/3 edge the dominant source of damping. As they are likely to be responsible for the lack of quasiparticle interference35,36, therefore preventing performing practical anyon braiding for the 2/3 FQHE state beyond \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
