In summary, exploiting microwave photo-assisted shot noise, our measurements provide the unambiguous determination of the tunneling charge at filling factor 2/3, while showing that DC shot noise approaches are unable to provide reliable e* determination at 2/3, solving the long-standing puzzle of e* increasing above e/3 at low temperatures. Microwave photo-assisted shot noise and two-particle dynamical interferometry offer insights into the charge dynamics of the ν = 2/3 edge at a mesoscopic scale. They also provide a practical estimate of the charge equilibration length \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${l}_{{eq}.}$$\end{document}leq., beyond which anyon braiding interferometry is likely to be unfeasible. Our findings align with models predicting that K-F-P neutral modes cannot propagate beyond \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${l}_{{eq}.}$$\end{document}leq. prompting a reevaluation of the role of neutral modes in previous experimental studies where \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${l}_{{eq}.}$$\end{document}leq. is significantly shorter than the relevant sample dimensions. Our approach is versatile and can be applied to a variety of quantum Hall phases exhibiting counter-propagating edge or interface60 modes, including those hosting non-Abelian anyons, as well as to other topological 2D materials at various filling factors.
